text: Monacycliones G−K and ent-Gephyromycin A, Angucycline Derivatives from the Marine-Derived Streptomyces sp. HDN15129 Yimin Chang, Li Xing, Chunxiao Sun, Shuang Liang, Tao Liu, Xiaomin Zhang, Tianjiao Zhu, Blaine A. Pfeifer, Qian Che, Guojian Zhang, and Dehai Li* ABSTRACT: Six new angucycline derivatives, named monacy- cliones G−K (1−5) and ent-gephyromycin A (6), as well as three known ones (7−9) were discovered from the marine sediment- derived actinomycete Streptomyces sp. HDN15129 guided by Global Natural Products Social (GNPS) molecular networking. Structures including absolute conﬁgurations were elucidated by extensive NMR, MS, and ECD analyses. Among them, monacyclione G (1) possesses a unique scaﬀold featuring a xanthone core linked to the aminodeoxysugar ossamine, and monacycliones H−J (2−4) are rare examples of natural angucyclines with an S-methyl group. Monacycliones I and J (3 and 4) showed cytotoxic activity against multiple human cancer cell lines, with IC50 values ranging from 3.5 to 10 μM. T he angucycline family of antibiotics, with more than 150

diﬀerent structures, is a group of aromatic polyketides that has grown signiﬁcantly since the ﬁrst example was isolated from Streptomyces rimosus the natural angucyclines can be divided into classical and nonclassical groups according to the cyclic skeletons. The major classical structures feature a typical benz[a]anthracene ring system.3 As for the nonclassical group, they represent oxidized or rearranged benz[a]anthracene skeletons such as the jadomycins with a pentacyclic benz[b]oxazolophenanthridine ring system and kinamycins with a 5-diazobenzo[b]ﬂuorene skeleton.6 Gen- erally, angucyclines structurally vary in the oxidation degrees of the core skeleton,3 and the position and type of substitutions including the saccharide (mostly O- or C-glycosides at rings A and D),3,5 hydroxy, and methylthio groups (rarely, with only three cases reported), etc.7−9 Consistent with the high structural diversity, angucyclines showed diverse bioactivities including antitumor and antibacterial properties.10−13 During our ongoing search for new bioactive molecules from actinomycetes,14−16 the metabolites of 10 marine-derived actinomycetes selected randomly were tentatively investigated by Global Natural Products Social (GNPS) molecular networking.17−20 Due to the visualized molecular clusters (nodes), the strain Streptomyces sp. HDN15129, which was indicated to have potentially new structures in the metabolite proﬁle, was selected for further exploration (Figure 1a). Guided by the HPLC-UV proﬁle (Figure S4) and cytotoxicity against K562 cancer cells (with 86% inhibition for the EtOAc extract at 100 μg/mL), fractionations and chemical investigation of the organic extract led to the isolation of six new compounds, named monacycliones G−K (1−5) and ent-gephyromycin A (6), along

HDN15129; (c) cluster corresponding to compounds of the angucycline family observed in the molecular network. The EtOAc extract (35.4 g) of strain Streptomyces sp. HDN15129 was fractionated by vacuum-liquid chromatography (VLC) on silica gel to obtain seven subfractions, which were further analyzed via the GNPS Web platform. A concentrated cluster with nodes attributed to fractions 4−7 was spotted within the whole molecular network (Figure 1b), and by querying the MarinLit database (http://pubs.rsc.org/marinlit) using the m/z values of 446.195, 462.189, and 464.205, the reasonable candidate molecules monacycliones A and B and frigocyclinone were identiﬁed, respectively. Further analysis of the cluster indicated putative new angucycline-related analogues. Guided by the LC-MS-UV analysis, six new analogues named monacycliones G−K (1−5) and ent-gephyromycin A (6), as well as three known angucyclines (7−9) were obtained by repeated column chromatography across silica gel, LH-20, and HPLC with ODS columns.

Monacyclione G (1), obtained as a brown amorphous powder, gave the molecular formula C26H27NO5 based on the HRESIMS spectrum. Detailed analysis of the 1D NMR data of 1 (Tables 1 and 2) revealed high structural similarity to the co- isolated monacyclinone A (7).12 The diﬀerence in 1 was the replacement of the carbonyl carbon (C-7) by an oxygen atom supported by the chemical shifts of C-6a (δ C 158.8) and C-7a C 144.1) (Table 2). The relative conﬁguration of the ossamine (δ sugar moiety in 1 was assigned by NOESY correlations. The cross-peaks among protons H-1′ax (δ H 1.98), H 1.43) revealed that H-1′, H-3′, and CH3-6′ were and H3-6′ (δ in an axial orientation. The NOESY correlations between H-2′ax (δ H 3.53) indicated that these two axial protons compared to H-1′ were on the opposite side of the aminosugar ring (Figure 3). Thus, the relative conﬁguration was determined as 1′R*, 4′S*, and 5′S*. To determine the absolute conﬁguration of the ossamine moiety, the optimized con- formations of (1′R,4′S,5′S)-1a and (1′S,4′R,5′R)-1b were obtained at the B3LYP/6-31+G(d) level and used for ECD calculations. Monacyclione K (5) and ent-gephyromycin A (6) were puriﬁed as brown amorphous powders with the molecular formulas C27H33NO9 and C19H18O8 on the basis of HRESIMS data, respectively. The 1D NMR data of 5 (Table 3) revealed the same fragment (C-1 to C-13) as gephyromycin A,24 except for the presence of the ossamine sugar moiety in 5 at C-9 (δ C 137.7) based on the HMBC signals from H-1′ (δ H 4.98) to C-9 and C- 10 (δ C 133.5) (Figure 2). The planar structure and relative conﬁguration of 6 were determined to be the same as those of gephyromycin A due to the almost identical chemical shifts (Table S2) and NOESY correlations (Figure S61). However, based on the opposite speciﬁc rotation values and ECD curves from those of gephyromycin A, compound 6 ([α]D 25 +50) was indicated to be the enantiomer of gephyromycin A ([α]D 25 −51). To prove the absolute conﬁguration of 6, the ECD spectra of (3S,4aS,6aS,12aR,12bR)-6a and (3R,4aR,6aR,12aS,12bS)-6b were calculated (Figure 7). Finally, the 3R, 4aR, 6aR, 12aS, 12bS absolute conﬁguration of 6 was evidenced by the good agreement of ECD curves between the experimental and the computational one of 6b. In summary, six new angucyclines were isolated from Streptomyces sp. HDN15129 under the guidance of GNPS. Previously, only three angucycline-type natural products (urdamycins E and V and sakyomicin E) containing a methylthio group7−9 and seven featuring the C-glycoside-linked aminodeoxysugar ossamine12,13 have been reported. In our ﬁndings, monacyclione G (1) is a nonclassical angucycline with a unique xanthone skeleton, while monacycliones H−J (2−4) are the ﬁrst naturally occurring C-glycoside-linked angucyclines having both a methylthio group and an aminosugar moiety. Monacyclione K (5) and ent-gephyromycin A (6) represent the rare cases with high oxidation degrees on rings A and B.23,27,28 Based on the cytotoxicity, the extra S-methyl group in monacyclione J (4) seems to improve the bioactivity compared with the non-sulfur counterpart frigocyclinone.13

General Experimental Procedures. Optical rotations were measured on a JASCO-1020 digital polarimeter. UV spectra were recorded on a Hitachi 5430 spectrophotometer. The ECD spectra were recorded on a JASCO J-715 spectropolarimeter. IR spectra were obtained on a Bruker Tensor-27 spectrophotometer in KBr discs. NMR spectra were collected on JEOLJN M-ECP 600 and Agilent 500 MHz DD2 spectrometers using tetramethylsilane as an internal standard. HRESIMS data were obtained using a Thermo Scientiﬁc LTQ Orbitrap XL mass spectrometer. Column chromatography was performed with Sephadex LH-20 (Amersham Biosciences). VLC was carried out over silica gel (Qingdao Marine Chemical Factory). MPLC was run using a C18 column (Bona-Agela CHEETAH HP100). HPLC was performed on an ODS column (YMC-Pack ODS-A, 10 × 250 mm, 5 μm, 3 mL/ min, YMC Co., Ltd.). Actinomycete Material. Streptomyces sp. HDN15129 (GenBank No. MN822699) was isolated from a sediment sample collected from the South China Sea (125°28.550′ E, 29°1.618′ N). The strain was deposited at the Key Laboratory of Marine Drugs, the Ministry of Education of China, School of Medicine and Pharmacy, Ocean University of China, Qingdao, People’s Republic of China. Fermentation and Extraction. The spores of Streptomyces sp. HDN15129 were inoculated into 500 mL Erlenmeyer ﬂasks containing 100 mL of culture medium composed of 0.5% peptone, 0.1% yeast extract, 0.1% glucose, 0.01% iron phosphate, and 0.3% calcium carbonate, pH = 7.0 (in seawater collected from Huiquan Bay, Yellow Sea), and cultured at 28 °C for 8 days on a rotary shaker at 180 rpm. A total of 50 L of broth was extracted with EtOAc (3× 20 L) to generate extract (35.4 g).

LC-MS/MS and Molecular Networking Analysis. LC-MS/MS analyses were performed using an UHPLC system (Ultimate 3000, Thermo Scientiﬁc) with a C18 column (ACQUITY UPLC BEH 1.7 μm, 2.1 × 100 mm, Waters) coupled to a hybrid Quadrupole-Orbitrap mass spectrometer (QExactive, Thermo Scientiﬁc). In positive-ionization conditions, the mobile phase consisted of 0.1% formic acid in H2O (A) and HPLC-grade MeOH (B). The elution gradient conditions for the LC mobile phase were as follows, based on times (t): t = 0−1 min, hold at 10% B; t = 1−23 min, increased linearly to 100% B; t = 23−26 min, hold at 100% B; t = 26−27 min, returned to initial conditions; t = 27− 30 min, hold at 10% B to re-equilibrate the column, which was delivered at 0.25 mL/min. The injection volume was 3 μL during the acquisition of positive polarity. The acquisition of H-ESI was carried out in data- dependent scan mode, sweeping from m/z = 70 to m/z = 1000. All MS/ MS data were converted to .mzXML format ﬁles by MSConvert software. Molecular networking was performed using the GNPS data analysis workﬂow and the spectral clustering algorithm. The spectral networks were imported into Cytoscape (ver. 3.6.1) for visualization. Isolation and Puriﬁcation. The extract was applied to a VLC column using a stepped gradient elution of MeOH−CH2Cl2, yielding seven subfractions (Fr.1−Fr.7). Computation Section. Conformational searches were run employ- ing the “systematic” procedure implemented in Spartan’14,29 using MMFF (Merck Molecular Force Field). All MMFF minima were reoptimized with DFT calculations at the B3LYP/6-31+G(d) level and B3LYP/TZVP level using the Gaussian09 program.30 The geometries were optimized starting from various initial conformations, with vibrational frequency calculations conﬁrming the presence of minima. Time-dependent DFT (TDDFT) calculations were performed on two lowest-energy conformations for 1a, six lowest-energy conformations for 2a, four lowest-energy conformations for 4a, and eight lowest- energy conformations for 6a (>5% population) for each conﬁguration using 20 excited states and using a polarizable continuum model (PCM) for MeOH. ECD spectra were generated using the program SpecDis31 by applying a Gaussian band shape with a 0.40 eV width for 1a, a 0.23 eV width for 2a, and a 0.30 eV width for 4a and 6a from dipole length rotational strengths. The dipole velocity forms yielded negligible diﬀerences. The spectra of the conformers were combined using Boltzmann weighting, with the lowest-energy conformations account- ing for about 96.8%, 99.9%, 99.7%, and 99.9% of the weights, respectively. The calculated spectra were shifted by +20 nm for 1a, −15 nm for 2a, and −10 nm for 4a and 6a to facilitate comparison to the experimental data. Cytotoxicity Assay. Cytotoxic activities of compounds 1−6 were evaluated against HL-60, K562 (using the MTT method), BEL-7402, HCT-116, SH-SY5Y, PC-3, U87, and ASPC-1 (using the SRB method) cell lines. ADM was used as a positive control, and the IC50 values are shown in Table 4. The detailed methodologies for biological testing have been described in previous reports.24,25
